##First-line doctor dictation: during the epidemic, instant noodles is the best friend

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

"I'm not afraid. We're medical professionals. I believe we can beat this epidemic. Just thinking of my family, i. . . " Dr. Tung choked up. We've been talking on the phone for half an hour about her work. She was still making fun of me, but when the word "home" was mentioned, her mood suddenly took a turn for the worse. I was a little flustered, said several "Hello Hello Hello" , but the phone was quiet for several minutes.

At last she began to speak again: "I am very depressed these days, but I can not cry in front of my family for fear that they will worry. I can not cry in front of the nurses. The nurses are young and I have to set an example for them. "
Illustration by Vincent Tan
To this day, she had not seen her child for fifteen days in a row. Dr. Tong is an attending physician in the Department of Traditional Chinese medicine at a basic-level hospital in Foshan, Guangdong. After the city closure in Wuhan, Guangdong Province launched a first-level response to major public health events. Her Hospital also temporarily organized a 24-member epidemic prevention working group, conduct primary screening of Febrile patients. Including 18 nurses and 6 doctors, including the entire hospital in each section of the capable force, even orthopedics, surgery has sent colleagues to support. She was a member of the team, and since the beginning of the new year, the entire team has been in quarantine, with no one ever coming home.
She is a very ordinary doctor, neither a front-line staff in Wuhan Infectious Disease Ward, nor the most critical ward doctor. In the vast sea of front-line medical personnel across the country, she is just the most inconspicuous drop of seawater. Her joys and sorrows are so ordinary, but in this extraordinary battle, her story is also the story of millions of people.
Here's what she said.

Dictation
By meow Kwai

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Dictation

By meow Kwai

To determine if he's a paramedic

Depends on his bladder

It was 10:30 in the middle of the night when we walked into the 24 hour, brightly lit fever clinic lobby. But I had to hurry to get to my work area within the allotted time to complete the handover with my colleagues coming off the night shift.

The entire fever clinic is about 200 square feet, but to enter my work area from the door, I had to go through three checkpoints: the clean area, the buffer area, and the quarantine area. First I have to put on my daily work clothes, the first mask and gloves in the cleaning area. Re-enter the buffer zone, put on a second mask and gloves, and change into protective clothing. Two masks were worn because the N95 was out of stock, and one mask would have sufficed if the N95 had been available. Finally, enter the quarantine area, wearing protective clothing and goggles.

Hand sanitization is performed for each action performed. The process is divided into twenty steps and involves a dozen sterilizations, all of which take at least half an hour or more to complete. Don't miss any steps. If you're not careful, you'll contaminate the sterile locker room.

Many of my colleagues'hands have turned white from too much disinfection. Even if the process of wearing protective clothing is very complicated, but this time no one colleagues will be delayed shift, everyone arrived on time, this is the most let me feel moved things these days.

At 11 a.m. , armed to the teeth, I went into my work area, opened my computer and looked at my work files. Every day, we had new things to learn, including the symptoms of new pneumonia, diagnostic criteria, and so on. In order to ensure ventilation, heating devices are not installed in fever clinics. It was cold at night and I wanted to drink some hot water, but as soon as I picked up the glass I put it down. Because from now until 8:00 tomorrow morning, I won't be able to go to the bathroom for nine hours.

Because the work needs, the work time must put on the goggles, in the cold winter day, the goggles are always separated by a layer of mist. (photo by Takaboshi)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Since the protective clothing is disposable, each time you go to the toilet, you have to change the protective clothing, which means you have to go through the process of entering the work area again. In order to save this time, almost all doctors don't go to the bathroom during office hours. We are only a basic hospital in Foshan, mainly responsible for the initial screening and screening of fever patients, the intensity of work is far lower than the doctors working in Wuhan designated hospitals, but we can only change off protective clothing when the shift change. The front-line doctors working in Wuhan receive dozens of times more than us every day. So they wear diapers in their Hazmat suits to save time in the bathroom.

We also hand out diapers at the hospital, but I resisted and would rather not eat, drink or go to the bathroom. We do three shifts, the day shift is from 8:00 am to 5:30 pm, and if you don't wear a diaper at all, it's going to be a huge challenge. One time when I was getting off work, the nurse came up to me and said, "are you sure you don't want to go to the bathroom? "? I shivered and said I wouldn't go and that I could take it. We often joke about this, such as during the shift change, shift change people say I am now hungry and tired, the next person will come to say: Also pee urgent. And the two of them laughed in unison.

In China, doctors have an unwritten consensus, to judge whether a person is a medical staff, the first look at his pounds bladder, the second look at his eating fast or not. Even when I make house calls, I rarely go to the bathroom during office hours, because there are more patients and fewer doctors, and I can't leave on time after a few trips to the bathroom. So the ability to hold the bladder is a long-term exercise out.

What's more, our inventory has been decreasing, we have six people on duty a day, at least six suits of protective clothing, and 12 N95 masks. Our hospital is not a designated hospital, in addition to fever clinic, other departments are also in synchronous operation. But other departments try to leave protective clothing and blindfolds to the front-line staff.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Expedition photography

They had no way to get Hazmat suits and had to wear white coats to work. Without goggles, they used their creative self-made protective masks. Male colleagues in the Radiology Department use used used old x-rays, tied two ropes, pad sponge on it. Women in Obstetrics and gynecology do the best, using clear plastic paper bags that can block droplets instead of goggles.

These days I'm more satisfied with my pound bladder function. I only used one suit per shift, so I didn't waste any supplies.

Not just during the epidemic

Being on call is a doctor's job

But Hunger and thirst gnawed at me until two in the morning and I was still wide awake. At night when there are no patients, we can lie down on the bed in the on-call room, but I can't sleep. I've been on duty all night for two nights in a row. I'm not tired, but I feel a little numb at work. If it had not been for this outbreak, I would have stood with my two children on the towering tower of Macao overlooking the Blue Bay, watching the pier lights one by one lit by night.

In fact, I had been on duty for more than forty consecutive days before I was notified of my transfer to the fever clinic. In fact, the medical staff is not the concept of holidays. Normally, we work in shifts. Because our department is short of staff recently, the weekend every week has become a single day off. In order to save out of the Lunar New Year's Day to the fourth holiday, the use of only one day off to help colleagues substitute work.

Until January 23, when the alarm sounded in the closing of the city of Wuhan, Guangdong Province initiated a level one response. Our Hospital also made a quick response, in two days to upgrade the fever clinic, and from all departments of the hospital medical staff, formed during the Lunar New Year epidemic working group. I worked in this hospital for nine years, and now I am an attending physician in the Department of Traditional Chinese medicine. I majored in breathing medicine as a graduate student, so I became the most suitable person for this department. My husband was very supportive of my work. He just said, you do your job, I'll take care of the kids.

It's not uncommon for doctors to suddenly cancel their vacations. My family has been used to my work. Doctors have to be on call at all times during off-duty hours. Every year when there is an outbreak of dengue fever or swine flu in Guangzhou, we always go to other outpatient clinics for support. Even on normal days, if my patient suddenly has a medical problem, i also need to be at the hospital in half an hour.

As soon as the response to the outbreak kicked in, the hospital went into a state of war. The head nurse was a strong woman in her forties who had not returned home for two days and nights. She was under the most pressure. Every Department of the hospital had to get in touch with her. New Year's Day fever clinic officially opened, divided into three relatively independent areas, the wall posted a detailed process, all the materials in place.

I have been working in the post of traditional Chinese medicine until New Year's Eve, the first day of the New Year to fever clinic report. These days on duty, especially hungry time will think of the New Year's Eve dinner, really delicious Ah. I didn't know it was going to be isolation the next day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph by Takaboshi

He was standing downstairs, waving at me

But I couldn't see his face for the life of me

The quarantine notice came on the first day of the Lunar New Year, the day I reported to the fever clinic. The battlefield of the epidemic is so volatile that none of us are prepared for it. The first day of the Lunar New Year is my 10th wedding anniversary with my husband. The second day of the Lunar New Year is my son's birthday. Even the accompanying clothes are packed by the family and sent to the dormitory downstairs. We were sequestered in hospital dormitories, a 5-10 minute walk to the fever clinic.

As the outbreak escalated, so did the concerns of the family. But I do know how to deal with family worries. I often send my kids pictures of me in my Hazmat suit and ask them, does mom look like teletubbies to you? I told my parents we were at the most secure workshop in the hospital. So far, no medical staff in Guangdong has been infected.

I also tell my husband on purpose: Jack Ma already has insurance for us, $20,000 for minor infections, and 14 days of vacation. Mild infections are as treatable as the common cold. It's a good deal. And $100,000 in the worst case. My husband laughed at my boredom and said he wasn't speaking to me. Actually, he knows I'm faking it.

One day when I was at work, my five-year-old daughter called me in tears. When I saw the video, her hand got caught in the door and turned black. I held back tears and whispered to her that I couldn't come home from work, so I hung up. Luckily, her husband was able to patch her up, and by the time I could answer the phone, the family was asleep.

After being quarantined, I will pick the best time to call my family every day, send wechat. But I rarely facetime with my family. Because when I looked in the mirror, my whole face was swollen, I had been strangled with a mask, my already sensitive skin began to break out in red rashes, and many of my colleagues, like me, were on allergy medication. My husband is not the kind of person who can sweet talk, he found that after not saying anything, drove from home to bring me a bunch of skin care products.

I was upstairs when he brought it in, but he had to go down to the security office, and I couldn't go down, so I had to watch him from the fourth floor window, and he was down there waving at me, but I couldn't see his face. After a while he drove off, and I looked out the window for a long time.

For a second, I was really homesick.

In the course of fighting the disease

Ramen is the doctor's best friend

I heard a lot of noise in the quarantine zone the other day. There's a sick man in the hall calling you names. YOU HAVE NO ETHICS! They are a family of five, Wuhan has a travel history, when entering Foshan, the police found the child abnormal temperature, so was sent to our hospital to wait for screening. But the adults insist that the child is not sick, refused to cooperate with screening. It happened that there were a lot of patients in the quarantine area that day. They waited for an hour and got impatient.

I was on duty in the cleaning area, patients are not too many, a link to the recent medical incidents I am very nervous, keep to report to the leadership of the situation. In a short while, the leadership informed the security guard, the police, after communication in accordance with their wishes, they will be sent to higher hospitals for treatment.

This thing goes away, we're still GONNA be nervous. While most patients understand a doctor's struggles, even a one in 10,000 risk is too much for a doctor to bear.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fortunately, so far our hospital has not found any positive cases. The country promulgates the policy, gives us the front-line staff daily 200 yuan-300 yuan subsidy. We didn't come here for the money, but it made us feel good, and the government really does a lot for health care workers.

The Sky began to light up. It was eight o'clock in the morning. I could leave work. Coming up, my first day off in over 50 days. On the first day of my isolation, my husband brought me a box of instant noodles to my dorm room. I didn't realize this box of Ramen was my greatest comfort in isolation.

There is a particularly popular photo on the Internet, Wuhan doctor's New Year's Eve dinner is instant noodles and egg Yolk Pie, the public very much love our doctor. In fact, even if you send us hot food, we can't eat it during office hours. One is to save time and avoid going to the toilet. Second, to avoid eating pollution, waste of scarce supplies. We often miss the canteen meal in three shifts. Our hospital is in the middle of nowhere. It's hard to order takeout during Chinese New Year. If we don't have instant noodles, we might not have hot food all day. Only instant noodles can be eaten at any time, and not afraid of bad. So instant noodles became our best friend during the war.

Coming back to the dormitory after work, eating instant noodles is like a ritual. I disinfected my hands, took a hot bath, and soaked all my clothes in chlorine. Then I cook on a instant noodles, Liu Chi, hot soup into the stomach, really very happy.
